# Vercel Speed Insights Installation

Successfully installed and configured Vercel Speed Insights for this Next.js project.

## Changes Made

### 1. Package Installation
- Installed `@vercel/speed-insights` package (version resolved by npm)
- Updated `package.json` with the new dependency
- Updated `package-lock.json` with locked dependency versions

### 2. Code Integration
Modified `/app/layout.jsx`:
- Added import: `import { SpeedInsights } from '@vercel/speed-insights/next';`
- Added `<SpeedInsights />` component in the body section, alongside the existing `<Analytics />` component

### Implementation Details

Following the official Vercel documentation (https://vercel.com/docs/speed-insights/quickstart), the integration was performed using the Next.js 13.5+ framework-specific instructions:

1. The SpeedInsights component is imported from `@vercel/speed-insights/next`
2. The component is placed in the root layout's body section
3. This follows the same pattern as the existing Analytics component

### Testing & Verification

✅ Build completed successfully (`npm run build`)
✅ No new linting errors introduced (ran `npm run lint`)
✅ Project structure and existing code patterns preserved
✅ Lock files properly updated

### Next Steps

To start seeing Speed Insights data in your Vercel dashboard:

1. Enable Speed Insights in your Vercel project dashboard:
   - Navigate to your project settings
   - Find "Speed Insights" in the sidebar
   - Click "Enable" for your project

2. Deploy the application:
   - Push changes to your Git repository, or
   - Run `vercel deploy` via the Vercel CLI

3. Monitor results:
   - After deployment and user visits, view performance metrics in your Vercel dashboard

## Files Modified

- `/app/layout.jsx` - Added SpeedInsights import and component
- `/package.json` - Added @vercel/speed-insights dependency
- `/package-lock.json` - Updated with locked dependency versions
